graph.pubchem_source_name: Haz-Map, Information on Hazardous Chemicals and Occupational Diseases

StringWithMarkup.String: Haz-MapÂ® is an occupational health database designed for health and safety professionals and consumers seeking information about the adverse effects of workplace exposures to chemical and biological agents.

The main links in Haz-Map are between chemicals and occupational diseases. These links have been established using current scientific evidence. Haz-Map classification provides the categories or classes of the chemical agents based on the activities, processes, and diseases.

Contains groupings of Adverse Effects
Decreased hemoglobin or number of red blood cells.
Chronic bronchitis is persistent coughing and production of phlegm for at least 3 months out of the year for at least two successive years. (American Thoracic Society).
Inducing tissue injury and fibrosis (scarring).

Primary hepatotoxins: the toxic effect to the liver is the principal adverse effect of the chemical. Secondary hepatotoxins: the potential for toxic effect in the occupational setting is based on cases of poisoning by human ingestion or animal experimentation.
Hepatotoxin, Primary - The toxic effect to the liver is the principal adverse effect of the chemical.
A substance that irritates the eyes and induces the flow of tears.
The presence of increased methemoglobin in the blood; the compound is classified as  primary toxic effect.
The chemical is potentially toxic to the kidneys in the occupational setting.

The chemical is toxic to nerve cells in the occupational settingÂincludes peripheral neuropathy (predominantly motor or sensorimotor), Parkinsonism, solvent syndrome (acute or chronic), and other CNS neurotoxins. [Rom, p. 697-707; LaDou, p. 386-96].
Other Poison

A chemical that is toxic to the reproductive system, including defects in the progeny and injury to male or female reproductive function. Reproductive toxicity includes developmental effects. See Guidelines for Reproductive Toxicity Risk Assessment.
Simple Asphyxiant - A gas or vapor that can cause asphyxiation by displacing oxygen, but at low concentrations has no other significant adverse effects.
Inflammation of the lungs induced by inhalation of metal fumes or toxic gases and vapors.

International Agency for Research on Cancer; classifies chemicals as established (1), probable (2a), or possible (2b) human carcinogens, or (3) not classifiable.
Occupational Asthma - Reversible bronchoconstriction (narrowing of bronchioles) initiated by the inhalation of irritating or allergenic agents.
Organochlorine Insecticide Poisoning - The organochlorine insecticides, including DDT and chlordane, persist in the environment and in animal tissues.

Organophosphate Insecticide Poisoning - Organophosphate insecticides interrupt nerve conduction. They cause the accumulation of acetylcholine at nerve endings by irreversibly binding with the acetylcholinesterase enzyme.
Pentachlorophenol/Dinitrophenol Poisoning - A chemical like pentachlorophenol that can cause a hypermetabolic state by poisoning cellular respiration (uncoupling oxidative phosphorylation).

Carbamate Insecticide Poisoning - The carbamate insecticides interrupt nerve conduction. They cause the accumulation of acetylcholine at nerve endings by reversibly binding with the acetylcholinesterase enzyme.
Central Nervous System Solvent Syndrome - Organic solvents can affect the central nervous system both acutely (increased reaction time and anesthesia) and chronically (permanent brain damage).
Allergic Contact Dermatitis - Dermatitis caused by contact with allergenic substances.
Methemoglobinemia, Primary - Methemoglobinemia (increased methemoglobin in the blood) is the primary toxic effect.
